    // after deleting any subset of elements and shifting the remaining elements left.
    // Let the remaining elements form a new array B. If B has length m, 
    // we want to maximize the count of indices j such that B[j] = j.

    // If we select a subsequence of nums, say at original indices i_1, i_2, ..., i_k,
    // where i_1 < i_2 < ... < i_k, this subsequence forms the new array B.
    // The element at B[j] is nums[i_{j+1}].
    // We want to maximize the count of j (0 <= j < k) such that nums[i_{j+1}] = j.

    // Let's rephrase the condition: If we keep nums[i] and it ends up at index j in the new array B, 
    // we want nums[i] = j.
    // If nums[i] = j, it means that exactly j elements before nums[i] (i.e., nums[i_1], ..., nums[i_j]) 
    // were kept from the original array nums, and i is the index of the (j+1)-th kept element.
    // The number of elements kept before i is j.
    // The original index of nums[i] is i.
    // The number of elements removed before i is i - j.
    // So, we are looking for the longest subsequence where if the element nums[i] is at index j, 
    // then nums[i] = j. This is equivalent to finding the longest subsequence where the element 
    // nums[i] matches its final index j.

    // This problem can be solved using a greedy approach, similar to finding the Longest Increasing Subsequence (LIS)
    // or by dynamic programming, but a greedy approach works here.

    // We want to select a set of indices S = {i_1, i_2, ..., i_k} such that i_1 < i_2 < ... < i_k,
    // and we maximize the count of j in {0, 1, ..., k-1} such that nums[i_{j+1}] = j.

    // Let's iterate through the original array nums. We maintain the target index 'target_index' 
    // for the next fixed point we are trying to form. Initially, the first fixed point must be at index 0.
    int target_index = 0;
    int count = 0; // The number of fixed points found so far (which is the current length of the subsequence)

    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        // If we choose nums[i] to be part of our final sequence, 
        // and it becomes the (target_index)-th element (0-indexed), 
        // we need nums[i] to be equal to target_index.
        if (nums[i] == target_index) {
            // We found a potential fixed point. We greedily accept it because keeping it 
            // allows us to potentially form a fixed point at target_index + 1 later, 
            // which is the best possible immediate gain.
            count++;
            target_index++; // The next required fixed point must be at the next index
        }
    }

    return count;
}
